The logarithm has 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left( 0,\infty \right)  \)
\end_inset 

 for its domain (it isn't defined elsewhere, at least in this course).
 Therefore, in 
\begin_inset Formula \( \ln \left( 4-x^{2}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

, we need to have 
\begin_inset Formula \( 4-x^{2}\geq 0 \)
\end_inset 

 or
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\label{sqrt4}
x^{2}<4.
\end{equation}

\end_inset 

 At this point, one must be 
\color red
careful
\color default
.
 We may think of taking the square root on both sides of equation 
\begin_inset LatexCommand \ref{sqrt4}

\end_inset 

 (getting 
\begin_inset Formula \( x<2 \)
\end_inset 

) and indeed, it is correct to do so...
 as long as you realize that if 
\begin_inset Formula \( a^{2}=b \)
\end_inset 

 then so does 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left( -a\right) ^{2}=b \)
\end_inset 

! That is, you have to consider negative values as well...
 Therefore, we have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x<2\]

\end_inset 

 
\color blue
and
\color default
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
x>-2.\]

\end_inset 

We conclude that the domain of 
\begin_inset Formula \( \ln \left( 4-x^{2}\right)  \)
\end_inset 

 is 
\begin_inset Formula \( \left( -2,2\right)  \)
\end_inset 

.
\newline 
As for the range of the function...
 we first have to look at the range of 
\begin_inset Formula \( 4-x^{2} \)
\end_inset 

